			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'm suprised no one has said it yet, but, if you haven't raided West yet, it's not very likely you are ready for North.  There's a *huge* difference between  West and North in difficulty level.  Also, if your guild is leveled up far enough to be in North, then you really don't need to be in West anyway (with the exception of Lendi for ST keys).
<br />

<br />
A simple way to look at it is probably this - Are the drops from Gozzrem and Telkorenar upgrades for most of your SK's and Pallies?  Then you are probably ready for West but not for North.  If you have access to better drops (SK weapon from Rhag2, for example), then you are probably mostly beyond Gozz and Telk.  About the same time you enter West, you should be killing Zlandicar (for drops and ST keys) and Ylandicar (mainly for ST keys).
<br />

<br />
I still believe a guild progression through ST is a good thing - The effect of Avatar-procing weapons should not be underestimated.  I think you should be starting ST about the same time you start NToV if you choose the ST path.  ST is a whole different conversation itself (which key dragons to kill, who to key, how to deal with the feeling of non-melee that shouldn't be keyed, etc.).
<br />

<br />
So let's say you're ready for West:
<br />

<br />
<ul><li>There are three named mobs in West - Gozzrem (easiest), Telkorenar (not much harder than Gozz), and Lendiniara the Keeper (requires strategy and practice).
<br />
<li>Coth'ing to Gozz and Telk are both interesting due to roamers that will agro onto your kos people.  The faster you can complete coth (and the smaller the crew needed to kill roamers), the better your chances for getting in there without wiping.
<br />
<li>Suggestion for starting out in West - Run all your non-kos to the west exit (near Lendi), hopefully when Lendi is not up.  Coth your remaining kos there.  Practice pulls and west armor farming at that exit so that you know what to expect from west-wurms.  They are a step up in difficulty from what you dealth with in HoT - AE's and attacks both.
<br />
<li>Once you can plow through Gozzrem and Telk, you are ready to try Lendi.
<br />
<li>Monks have it the hardest on faction - A non-kos monk really makes the Lendi clearing a whole lot easier.  Our pullers worked hard in Kael keeping their faction up between West runs.  Plan on them /q'ing out (or zoning out in the case of Lendi) to avoid the big faction hits.  Sorry mages, but the Kael helms and toes should go to monks first since it's far more difficult for them to avoid taking the faction hits in the first place.
<br />
<li>As a mage, unless you have a lot of free time on your hands for fixing faction, don't attack the trash mobs at all, and make sure you will have the abillity to zone our /q out on the big mobs to avoid faction hits.  The fact that you will have a kos mage there for things like mod-rods is good.
<br />
<li>More specific strategies for each of the mobs can be found elsewhere - No need to cover that here.</ul>
<br />
If you're ready for North, here are some suggestions for a coth mage there:
<br />

<br />
<ul><li>Make your feign classes and non-kos folks aware that they should not go afk for extended periods of time.  Try to give them some idea of when coth will start so they can take breaks as needed up to that point.  Getting an entire guild across WW individually becomes a whole lot more difficult once you go kos -- Those that get to ToV early often take extended afk's since they know it will be a while before the guild is ready to start North.
<br />
<li>Try to get sow right before you zone into ToV - The faster you make it past Ikatiar's room on your way to the coth spot, the better.  This isn't critical, just something I've always felt more comfortable having.  Also, with sow, I've actually been able to run all the way out the west exit with agro from Ikatiar.  Fun run, let me tell you <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />.  There's no way I would have made it without sow.  (Remember, it can't be SoE since lev doesn't work in ToV.)
<br />
<li>On arrival in ToV, send tells to buffers to get you buffed up first so you can go ahead and get in coth position - Get mana buffs of all sorts (enchanter, druid, beastlord), a symbol from a cleric (optional), and FR/CR resist buffs if they are higher than yours.
<br />
<li>Once you are buffed, invis up - I can't stress this enough.  Amazingly enough, Ikatiar's guards usually do not see through invis (although sometimes they do).  If you are going to die on the way to the coth spot, it's usually from Ikatiar's guards.
<br />
<li>When you get inside the NToV door, turn right and hug the wall on the left as you go around the corner.  The further you stay away from the room on the east, the better - This is Ikatiar's room.
<br />
<li>As you approach the steps ahead, start moving away from the walls, more into the center of the stairs.
<br />
<li>Once through the door at the top of the stairs, hug the right wall now.  Stay far away from Eashen's room.  The chickens you'll be passing aren't kos-to-all, but Eashen is.
<br />
<li>Proceed up the ramp, around the corner, but don't go too far -- Aaryonar's ("Roy" commonly) guards are kos.  Move to the west wall to start coth - not for your benefit, but for that of those you are calling.
<br />
<li>First to be coth'd are any who are non-kos or can feign.  Yes, the non-kos can run in themselves, but, unless they have practice doing it as you will, they'll be likely to agro Iki along the way.  Better to just coth them all.
<br />
<li>At first, you might still have non-kos clerics and tanks - Eventually they'll all end up kos, of course.  Once your non-kos/feign are called, get a cleric, a tank, and an enchanter/shaman in the group for coth.  Announce to the raid that you are about to start clearing the chickens.  Call the warrior first - He'll get agro from two chickens immediately.  Call the cleric next, who will heal the warrior and likely end up with agro from 2 of the 3 chickens as a result.  Hopefully you had at least two SK's feigned up there - They should grab the other two chickens.  Get your slower called next, and you're all set.  Get another mage in the group 4th - Coth them so that you can double your coth rate at that point.  Get one or two more clerics up next, then everyone else.
<br />
<li>Make certain that *no one* gets in line of sight of the ramp once the chickens are engaged - The chickens on the ramp will assist.  A fight with 3 chickens is easy - 10 is a wipe.  The raid leader should be yelling "LINE OF SIGHT" until it finally sinks into everyone's mind.  This will be your single biggest source of wipes on coth until people get it right.
<br />
<li>You'll start out in North doing Eashen and Ikatiar for a while.  Eventually, another guild may leave Roy down and some other North named up beyond him so that you can venture furture in.  However, most guilds are going to be smart and kill the easy mobs on the east after killing Roy, so you won't have much to get to anyway.
<br />
<li>Eventually, you'll be ready for Roy - He's a booger.  Probably the second hardest of the normal North mobs (probably the hardest).  If you can kill Roy, all of North will be open to you, and the real fun begins.</ul>
<br />
And the biggest tip of all for a coth mage in ToV (and this really applies anywhere) - Cannipet between every coth.  Due to the long recycle time on coth, you have almost exactly the right amount of time to cast one 49 earth or ms pet and reclaim it before the coth spell gem ungrays.  You can likely coth most of your raid without running out of mana as long as you canni between each coth.  Of course, don't cast a pet for canni when there's an AE mob around - The pet will agro and you will take a faction hit.
<br />

<br />
Ok, one last thing - You said that you'll be playing your shaman in north after the mage is camped when coth is done.  Just realize that if you want to log in your mage to loot anything, he'll need to be dragged to the raid by an SoS rogue due to respawn.  Once in North, pretty much everything is kos to *everyone*.  You won't be able to walk him to catch up with your raid.  Also, not sure what level your shaman is, but I *highly* recommend that you not even think about North unless you are 59+ (preferably 60).  As HoT AE's require around 54-55 to resist at a reasonable rate - The North AE's are 59-60.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
